column4: spasms.  the cold made me more painful so i had to leave florida again to come home for the warmth
column7: care from my friends and neighbors.  it's been relaxing and sweet meeting old and new friends on my gime. no rush. just taming it easy!! we need to stop the crime though. too much gun shots all over even in florida when i was there.  it's too much crime in our country and we need it to stop spoiling up the place. come to jamaica to reinvest so that people have more things to do and places to go. i have been advocating for alot since i was young growing up in negril westmoreland jamaica especially after growing up around hustlers
column8: tourists and people of all types. i love to encourage you to save
column10: be well and live life to the fullest. it's a shame how much it if us go through and people get away with murder but that's been our world. if we don't keep talking about things or stand up for our rights then things will not change.  change can come so let's unite
column13: unity and humanity vibes. love and sunshine hugs

column2: am i the only one who draws monsters to represent my negative thoughts?

column1: you may wanna give this a try! you would be surprised by how much this simple activity can help you realize that your negative thoughts are just that
column2: thoughts! they’re not true representations about who you are as a person!

column1: meet my shame monster! he may look like a children’s cartoon drawing but don’t be fooled by this guy.
he sometimes hovers over me making me feel small and at times
column2: causing me to believe i’m not good enough.

column1: and everyone has one of these! nobody is immune. they like to creep out when we think about trying something new! or when we need to buy a dress or swim suit! sometimes they crawl out when the topic of motherhood comes up. mine has totally started crawling out as i begin to age
column2: what with new wrinkles and unwanted hair! #amiright
i have dreams and goals and a life i want to live and no inner monster is gonna get in my way.

column1: and you’ve got a life to live too!
on my last blog post i opened up about a time when my monster made a viscous appearance and i follow it up with the steps i used to get out from underneath him.
learning how to get out from underneath our shame monsters is key to living a life of happiness!
we can not go on believing we aren’t pretty enough
column4: good enough if we are going to live life to the fullest. we must find ways to get above these thoughts and feelings when they creep in.

column2: which for me just screams “you already know what you have to let go of.” and it was interesting
column5: or something that i thought i’d want to hold onto this time
column6: as the death card usually shows up for me ... no
column7: this card wants me to release the narrative around my trauma
column9: and the negative feelings i’ve held around myself since my assaults three years ago - things i’ve held onto because they’re comfortable. the negativity was how i made sense of all of it
column10: and the pain those thoughts caused me to feel somehow felt like a way of proving my strength to the world
column11: as being a survivor became the biggest part of my identity. but i finally shared a piece of my writing this week which i’ve been holding onto secretly for three years
column12: a piece which was basically my way of showing people how much i hated myself for what happened
column13: how often i questioned myself during the process of seeking justice and all that ugly stuff. and it felt so fucking good to just let it go. to say
column16: and i experienced all this pain
column17: and thought all these nasty things about myself”
column18: and to then let all that go as i put it down on paper. i’m looking forward to letting go of more of my comfort as i dig deep into the parts of my identity that deserve to be written about and released
column19: and i’m really grateful i’m starting to learn how to embrace the lesson of death in this way. if anyone’s interested in reading the piece i wrote
column20: it’s a little too personal for the blog just yet
column21: but i’d be happy to share if you want to shoot me a dm💕✨ i’m trying to actually complete & publish it  eventually so i’d really love any feedback from fellow writers 🧚🏼‍♀️

column12: a piece which was basically my way of showing people how much i hated myself for what happened
column13: how often i questioned myself during the process of seeking justice and all that ugly stuff. and it felt so fucking good to just let it go. to say
column16: and i experienced all this pain
column17: and thought all these nasty things about myself”
column18: and to then let all that go as i put it down on paper. i’m looking forward to letting go of more of my comfo as i dig deep into the pas of my identity that deserve to be written about and released
column19: and i’m really grateful i’m staing to learn how to embrace the lesson of death in this way. if anyone’s interested in reading the piece i wrote
column20: it’s a little too personal for the blog just yet
column21: but i’d be happy to share if you want to shoot me a dm💕✨ i’m trying to actually complete & publish it  eventually so i’d really love any feedback from fellow writers 🧚🏼‍♀️

column2: and have the pleasure of welcoming jenny randhawa to this year's women's day program (we've literally been chatting about this for years!). .

column1: jenny graduated with a master's in health administration from ubc in 2005. with eight years of management consulting experience
column2: a strong background of education and practical experience
column3: it’s no wonder that she has become a force to be reckoned with in the business world. in 2007 jenny decided to tackle new territory — the beauty industry. when blo blow dry bar launched in 2007
column4: jenny was the first to be considered for a franchise partnership and has been with the company since day one
column5: savouring the successes and learning and perfecting the ropes. following the success of her first bar in early 2010
column6: jenny acquired all 3 of vancouver’s blo bars six months later as well as the rights to all of british columbia
column7: striking while the (curling) iron was hot! since then
column8: jenny continues to lead this multi-unit company demonstrating her strengths in all aspects of business management including operations
column13: organizational structure as well as strategic planning. in 2019
column14: blo corporate recognized her as a leading franchise partner out of 130+ blo locations in social media management
column16: retention and culture and outstanding contributor to operational growth strategies. her greatest passion is to provide one-on-one support and guidance to her fellow entrepreneurs.

column2: i’m denise. i’ve got some new friends on my social platforms so i felt called to re-introduce myself and what it is i do. ⁣

column1: i’m a self-healing badass and i love empowering and working with women who want to do the same for themselves. ⁣

column3: i’m doing great. keep reading). years later
column4: i was sexually assaulted by a friend and 8 months later
column5: my mom passed away. i worked my butt off in college to numb out my feelings (as i’m sure many of us are familiar with) and did what i needed to do to survive. ⁣

column2: i had a massive awakening. i realized how much of my life was a facade. i played by all the rules of society yet deep down
column3: i was angry. i constantly had anxiety attacks
column4: desensitized my emotions with food and drugs
column5: and would burst out in anger over the smallest things. ⁣

column1: while i never got physically sick
column2: my emotional and energetic “bodies” were toxic. ⁣

column1: l learned to heal myself through a variety of energy healing modalities. my healing practices started with yoga
column6: oracle cards and vulnerability through sisterhood. i had so many mentors and healers who helped me along the way and i’m forever grateful for their wisdom and guidance. ⁣

column1: what made the most impact though
column2: was meditation and connecting to what was truly within me. ⁣
lots of shame and grief. then anger. then guilt and sadness. finally
column3: forgiveness. there were also a bunch of non-serving beliefs such as “i’m not worthy of my mother’s love

column1: i felt all the feelings and integrated the lessons i needed to learn from having those beliefs and experiences. ⁣
this process took me a whole year. ⁣
i now believe that i am already whole
column2: already perfect and already enough to be the fullest version of myself and walk the path of my purpose.⁣

column1: my purpose is to continue healing myself while guiding others along their own path of self-healing. ⁣

column1: 5255;instagram;2019-03-01 23:05:36;FALSE;"it’s been a whirlwind of emotions for me today.
after some pre-spring cleaning i came across a big envelope labeled “important papers” and naturally took a peek to see what the contents inside were. .

it was basically my childhood packed into one envelope. there were statements my “friends” had written against me while i was in high school for a fight i was in. long lists of my arrests. records of the foster homes i stayed in during my early teen years. the papers i received upon being discharged from a juvenile detention center. my certificate of adoption. my medical evaluation after a traumatic sexual abuse in 2006 and letters from my therapist after years of helping me cope. 🙏🏻 the list goes on.. .
it made me so sad at first to read these things and i deep in my heart wanted to cry for my younger self. however
column3: the more i thought wow.... i’ve really come a long way. .

column1: some of you might not know my whole story and i’ll save that for a later date
column2: but today i want you to remember that you are not your past and your circumstances or upbringing have no power in creating your future. that’s all up to you. and you’re worthy of it all. ♥️

column1: 5287;instagram;2019-03-01 23:45:56;FALSE;today i finally put myself in front of the camera and snapped some self portraits for my bio as a contributor to a new online community for women called @theandsociety. i have been thinking a lot this week about social media
column2: and the ways in which we use it to build connections with the world around us. i recently decided to open up my family’s life and share intimate details of our traumas and our challenges because i truly believe that like brene brown says
column3: “you either walk into your story and own your truth
column4: or you live outside of your story
column5: hustling for your worthiness.” when you share your story in the public arena - it can be sometimes misconstrued and misinterpreted as a need for attention and affirmation or an exploitive move. when we as adults decide to open up our children’s lives and share their stories and identities in the public arena we are subject to scrutiny from the public on our motives for doing such a thing. this week i shared my sons struggle with #dyslexia
column6: and there were moments that i wondered if his story was mine to tell
column7: and if he would some day resent me for choosing to do so. but then came the hundreds of comments
column8: messages and emails from so many who read his story and felt inspired to share their own experiences with rejection
column10: and overcoming adversity. a single story ignited memories and past experiences in family members
column11: friends and strangers from all over the globe that supported us in the most meaningful and powerful of ways. there is nothing more #healing than #metoo - and until you have the courage to declare your pain out loud - you can’t open yourself for these kinds of connections. it was through the incredible vulnerability of @teresa.swanstorm.anderson that i stumbled upon her story and connected with her via social media. it was from that connection with a stranger that i was brought into a circle and a community of women that i have been in desperate need of for far too long. the social media world we live in can be cruel and hard and filled with all kinds of terrible things - but it can also provide you with support and a community that makes the world feel like such a fantastic place. thank you 🌎;;en;#dyslexia

column1: 5331;instagram;2019-03-02 00:40:02;FALSE;"trigger warning ⚠️ this post contains talk of and descriptions of sexual violence.

when @adornia offered to send me one of their lariat necklaces they gave me the option of choosing my own words as part of their #adorniaspeakup campaign. there were a lot to choose from but when i saw the #metoo necklace i knew immediately that that was the one i wanted. not only because it's something so personal to me
column2: but because one hundred percent of the profits are donated to @rainn which is the largest nonprofit anti-sexual assault organization in america. it was an easy choice at the time. but the campaign is about letting people know what the words on the necklace mean to me and now that it's time to actually do that in a very public forum it feels a lot more difficult. the founder of #adornia

column1: 5371;instagram;2019-03-02 02:10:34;FALSE;"this morning as i was curling my hair a swift of sadness came over my heart. i cried and cried. you know why? i cried for the countless of women who are alone in their comfort zone. i crawled out of my comfort zone by coming back to michigan! 😳

i'm talking to the women and girls that are alone out of survival. afraid of being hurt. afraid of being abused. afraid of their divine purpose. its worst to be surrounded by people and still feel alone. don't get me wrong there are women that need to be alone for real for real.  women who have healed can stand alone in the dark never pour from a empty cup. 💕

meaning i dont believe giving advice that i have not practiced daily mentally and emotionally.🙏 i've earned the heart to speak my truth as i know it. humbly i went somewhere and got my inner life together.  i feel for every single mother and their daughters who are fighting life alone.
no woman should suffer in depression alone.
you are divine love made by god.
if you didnt know that well...now you know!

column1: breathwork is a powerful tool to calm the mind
column2: bring peace to the mind and body
column3: and it opens the heart to a deeper connection to self and others!

column1: we live in a world of so much stress
column2: so much “going on” inside and outside of us…this is a time to do some self care and self love
column3: drop and in let go of the mind
column4: even go into no mind if you will
column5: where thoughts stop and the breath takes over and everything is still within. this is where healing can happen…not only in the stillness of the mind
column6: but also in the increase of oxygen in the system…as the oxygen carries away so much of the past and negative patterns and beliefs we sometimes hold onto.

column1: since it is a deep breath
column2: it gets into those deep places within that sometimes is even hidden to us
column3: those areas that hold emotions…and we can be a store house of all kinds of emotions…with breathwork
column4: breath by breath we release what is stored inside so we can come back to our whole selves
column5: our aliveness…and it unveils our true selves!

column1: getting ready to release this as the first single off the album.  i wrote this song about loving someone for who they are and everything they come with...mess and all...so i called it “a beautiful mess”. it wouldn’t be til’ a couple years later that i realized it was song about me and i was the beautiful mess i was singing to.  so i decided to change the title to “i’m a beautiful mess”. sometimes it’s like that...we go out of our way and try hard to give and receive love from everybody else...when maybe we should try giving it to ourselves.  and if that describes you (or described you)...i want you to know you are a beautiful mess and we love to love you...messy and all 💜😉#youareenough
stay tune for the release and help us donate half the profits to the east la women’s center 👸🏽💪🏾💜

壊れた瞬間についに家にまで来たかと思った
例え壊した本人の家の管理会社が修理費を払ったとしても

column1: 5493;instagram;2019-03-02 06:24:35;FALSE;"this time last year i marched with some of my nearest and dearest in the 40th anniversary of mardi gras. this year i find myself in the us missing my friends and family
column2: but living a very lucky life to say the least.

column1: mardi gras for me represents a celebration of all things diverse and i know there are people that have fought long and hard for that privilege and will continue to do so. to those i am thankful and eternally grateful.
i’m fortunate to be part of the rainbow community and i acknowledge there are other communities and groups that suffer under similar circumstances. the fight is not over.
i know i live in a bubble of support from friends and family that others are not so fortunate to have. to all of you i thank and love you and know you are loved.
i say to the bigots and ignorant people of this world. grow the fuck up!
be the change and accept people for who they are for the world will be a better place. i need not mention the naysayers who are now convicted of crimes beyond belief.
to those that feel alone and isolated
column2: know that it does get better. there are people that love you and will support you. you are not alone. find your family.
when the sharpest words wanna cut me down

and i'm marching on to the beat i drum
i'm not scared to be seen

🤩 | new respawn van leaked! 💵 | use code 'dailyfn' with @epicgripz
🤩 | new respawn van leaked! 💵 | use code 'dailyfn' with picgripz
具体的な事以外から書くと
2017年年末から通勤、帰宅時に普通に横断歩道を渡っていたら車が突っ込んできてギリギリで止まった。
2018年年始以降は通勤、帰宅時に絶え間なく不審な車が歩道で路駐していた
帰宅時は冬なので暗く通り過ぎる瞬間にヘッドライトを当てられたり、
同じく通り過ぎる瞬間にエンジンをかけ音で監視してるよというアピールが毎日あった
その中にはパトカーもいた
つまり管轄の#尼崎東警察署にも手を回されていた
‪警察に狙われる覚えもないし‬
#警察 ってお金で動いてくれるんやって思った
もしくはヤンマーが私に対する虚偽の報告をして見張るように言ったか
でも捜査なら私にバレないところに止まるはず
明らかに視界に入る所に止まっていたから
それもあり社内での違法行為があっても
その事では警察に相談しても無駄だと思った
角から急に人や車や自転車が飛び出してきて
いつぶつかってもおかしくなかった
危ないが自転車が1番便利なのと
早く家に着くので乗っていたが
徐々に徒歩やバス通勤に変えて
最終的には朝乗ろうと思ったら自転車がパンクしていて
2018年8月に完全にバス通勤に変更し会社に申請した
そのバスも早く出勤しようとしても30分の遅延、
銀行やコンビニに寄ろうと少し早く出ても遅延

column1: 具体的な事以外から書くと
2017年年末から通勤、帰宅時に普通に横断歩道を渡っていたら車が突っ込んできてギリギリで止まった。
2018年年始以降は通勤、帰宅時に絶え間なく不審な車が歩道で路駐していた
帰宅時は冬なので暗く通り過ぎる瞬間にヘッドライトを当てられたり、
同じく通り過ぎる瞬間にエンジンをかけ音で監視してるよというアピールが毎日あった
その中にはパトカーもいた
つまり管轄の#尼崎東警察署にも手を回されていた
‪警察に狙われる覚えもないし‬
#警察 ってお金で動いてくれるんやって思った
もしくはヤンマーが私に対する虚偽の報告をして見張るように言ったか
でも捜査なら私にバレないところに止まるはず
明らかに視界に入る所に止まっていたから
それもあり社内での違法行為があっても
その事では警察に相談しても無駄だと思った
角から急に人や車や自転車が飛び出してきて
いつぶつかってもおかしくなかった
危ないが自転車が1番便利なのと
早く家に着くので乗っていたが
徐々に徒歩やバス通勤に変えて
最終的には朝乗ろうと思ったら自転車がパンクしていて
2018年8月に完全にバス通勤に変更し会社に申請した
そのバスも早く出勤しようとしても30分の遅延、
銀行やコンビニに寄ろうと少し早く出ても遅延
朝は普通に来たことないんじゃないかという記憶がある
バス会社にも手を回されていた
私が何をしても先に関係する企業に
手を回し嫌がらせをされていた

column1: 5523;instagram;2019-03-02 07:37:18;FALSE;"but wylie wasn’t just talking about fashion. he had recently been exposed to a new discipline: “information operations”
column4: air and space in the us military’s doctrine of the “five-dimensional battle space”. his brief ranged across the scl group – the british government has paid scl to conduct counter-extremism operations in the middle east
column5: and the us department of defense has contracted it to work in afghanistan.

column1: i tell him that another former employee described the firm as “mi6 for hire”
column2: and i’d never quite understood it.

column1: - it’s like dirty mi6 because you’re not constrained. there’s no having to go to a judge to apply for permission. it’s normal for a ‘market research company’ to amass data on domestic populations. and if you’re working in some country and there’s an auxiliary benefit to a current client with aligned interests
when i ask how bannon even found scl
column2: wylie tells me what sounds like a tall tale
column3: though it’s one he can back up with an email about how mark block
column5: happened to sit next to a cyberwarfare expert for the us air force on a plane. - and the cyberwarfare guy is like
column7: you should meet scl. they do cyberwarfare for elections.’

column1: it was bannon who took this idea to the mercers: robert mercer – the co-ceo of the hedge fund renaissance technologies
column2: who used his billions to pursue a rightwing agenda
column3: donating to republican causes and supporting republican candidates – and his daughter rebekah.

column1: 5561;instagram;2019-03-02 09:15:25;FALSE;"room-owning women of 2019: christine lagarde. i love christine lagarde! md of the international monetary fund (imf) since 2011. she has wonderful quiet
column2: confident energy. so much grace. authority worn very lightly. she has to give a lot of very long and boring speeches and i think she knows this and is amused by it. (in some jobs you have to accept the necessary boring nature of some speaking. a full one-hour imf report is not going to be like olivia colman at the oscars. it will be comprehensive
column4: data-packed. so important to know what “success” looks like. sometimes “everyone thought it was boring and unremarkable” constitutes 100% success.) this week she gave an interview to mark international women’s day reminding us that (look away now
column5: people) 59 countries around the world still have no laws against sexual harassment. in 18 countries it is not illegal to prevent women from working. her argument was that (a) #metoo is great but it’s barely relevant in some parts of the world because there is so much work to do on gender and (b) she is concerned that the conversation around #metoo will make conservative (small c) employers even more conservative — so we must continue to talk about these things in a nuanced way and scrutinise hiring patterns. lessons from her speaking: it’s ok to bring levity
column7: “small talk” (she loves to mention the weather) into serious (actually quite boring) professional speeches. if you have a serious message
column8: don’t be afraid to keep it simple and tight and deliver it slowly and without drama
column9: using the smile and brightness in your voice to stop it from being too dull. (i wish t may would do this. but then i wish t may would do a lot of things.) stillness of the body and the head (nb not stiffness!!!) is so powerful: balance this with animation in your face (smile!) and warm eye contact. easy! ;) #howtoowntheroom #authorsofinstagram #bookstagram #bemorechristine #maylagardebewithyou";;en;#MeToo

column1: 5596;instagram;2019-03-02 10:23:43;FALSE;"this week @nbcbrooklyn99 addressed the issue of #metoo. as a result of the episode i have had conversations with men around me about the common occurrence of sexual harassment and abuse. literally every woman i know has had some experience with it.
what's really standing out about these conversations
column3: is that many good men feel sick that they can't relate to or understand what it's like to be a woman and to have these experiences.

column1: you can't know. don't blame yourself for not knowing what something is like when you have not experienced it first hand. and to be honest
column2: i'm happy you don't know first hand. i'm happy for you.

column1: why is this my response? because i am a lover of people. i don't discriminate between gender
column2: race or sexual orientation. we all have privileges and we all have pain. i'm rooting for all people

column1: does this mean that i deny these issues?

column2: no!! the issues are real and the key is vulnerable #communication. as long as you keep attacking people for what they don't understand
column3: they will understand it even less and resist it even more.

column1: thank you @stephaniebeatriz for directing this amazing episode. beautiful writing. great job.";;en;#metoo.

column1: رفع النجم جوني ديب البالغ من العمر 55 عاما دعوى قضائية ضد طليقته آمبر  بسبب مقال كتبته لصحيفة a washington post في ديسمبر عام 2018 عن تعرضها للعنف المنزلي.
ووفقا للدعوى القضائية فإن الممثلة الأمريكية كتبت مقالها كشخصية عامة تعرضت للعنف المنزلي ولم تذكر اسم جوني ديب بالتحديد ‏ ‏ ‏

ووصفها جوني بالكاذبة وأنها مجرد خدعة متقنة من آمبر لكسب التعاطف معها ولتحقيق تقدم في مسيرتها المهنية حيث قال جوني ديب"" هيرد ليست ضحية للعنف المنزلي بل مجرمة"" مدعياً أن الممثلة الأمريكية هي التي اعتدت عليه. ‏ ‎‏ ‏
ويقول جوني ديب إن المقال قد أثار ضررا في حياته المهنية، مدعيا أنه بعد مرور 4 أيام فقط على نشر المقال تم استبعاده من pirates of the caribbean، وأصبحت هي محبوبة من قبل حركة #metoo. ‏
وانا اقوووول ليش تم استبعاد جووني من سلسلة
حاليا يحاول ان ياخذ تعويض قدره ٥٠ مليون على

column1: picture 2: poem in swedish posted by @stinawollter

column2: for a pretty long time now
column3: fought for women’s right and for equality for different kind of minority-groups. this very day i can really feel how important it is
column4: it’s just not a fight for the popular-culture
column5: don’t ever degrade this fight to something that small. it’s a fight that’s been going on for decades and decades... and it’s truly a fight that has to be taken seriously. for many this is a question about life or death! in many countries and in many relationships you can risk your life as a woman
column8: as a ethnic minority etc... the poisonous patriarchy has done enough damage on this earth
column11: donald trump is the fucking president of the united states? it’s insane.

column1: we don’t need this culture anymore
column2: we don’t need to hear arguments from people that minimizes our rights as women or as a minority. we need to be valued as much as white cis-gendered males
column4: our education or what our profession is. we don’t need more opinions about how a woman “should” be to be a good or a bad feminist
column5: we just need equal and basic human rights. all of us. this world needs to change and i really would love to live to see that day. millions of people before us have fought to help us come this far and i think the poems here really state that we have power to move forward
column6: to make this world a loving and respectful place to live in.

column2: a group of 30 bangaloreans gathered at our courtyard to discuss the art vs artist issue
we have been pondering over how to look at the issue
column3: whether to dismiss art created by artists accused of misdeeds
column4: or view an artwork as having its own life

column1: in a most engaging discussion moderated by pavithra sankaran
column2: we managed to touch upon various aspects of the problem by creating a safe space for conversation. from the role of the individual vs collective opinion
column3: to the role of social media in today’s outrage culture
column4: to the sharing of experiences and thoughts on the matter
column5: it was a wholesome discussion that brought up and addressed some essential questions
column6: as well as threw light on the grey areas.

column2: it was not easy to come to one conclusion or solution given the vastness of the topic. here are a few thought-provoking questions that came up which we’d like to leave you to think about: -what are the implications of separating an artwork from the artist? -in the #metoo era
column3: do artworks made my wrongdoers deserve a place in museums and galleries? -by appreciating or looking at a work made by a known miscreant
column4: are you enabling the perpetrator? -is boycotting and public shaming the only way to tackle this issue? or are there more humane solutions like reforms? -finally
column5: what is your take on the issue?

column1: you can share your thoughts in the comments section or email us atinfo@thecourtyardcommunity.in. we hope to have many more such open discussions in the near future.

#尼崎東警察署 もパトカーを
一台も2台も無駄に使い相当ヒマ何だなとも思っていた。
他にする事あるだろう
困ってる人いるだろうと
バス通勤に変えたので
#jr西日本 のicocaを申し込んだら
窓口で9月でポイント制度が廃止になりますと言われた
ここまで意地悪をされるんだと愕然とした
多分それによって他にも困るお客さんがいるはずだけどそんな事構わないんだろう
問題の2018年1月13日のuntitledグッズ販売に行く日も
なぜわかったのか不思議だったが
会社に来ているリクルートの派遣の同じ嵐ファンの子にいつ行くんですか？
とスマホを手に持ちながら聞かれた
お財布と相談と答えたが
多分それがわかった原因ではと思っている
最近テレビで#リクルート のcmを見るのも
そのせいだと思っている
私が見そうな番組をわかっている
又は娘がチャンネルをそこに変える
家でテレビを見てても脅迫されてる気分だ
またそれを聞いてきた塩崎さんと言う同じ名字の男性が
2018年6月か7月に#社長室 に異動になっている
特に調べてはないけど
タイミング的に親戚か？
派遣として入ってきたのは
#untitled も落選 それからの話

column1: 5690;instagram;2019-03-02 12:46:53;FALSE;"i had such a great time reading this book.... #dieletztentagedespatriachats by @marga_owski

column2: what i could be about. it's not about cooking recipes and knitting patterns for sure.

column1: the book is a collection of columns by german-polish journalist margarete stokowski for a time frame of roughly the last 4 to 5 years commenting on all the things happening in that time like the refugee crisis
i really love her writing style
column2: it's like you're sitting on the couch with a glass of wine
column4: not like reading a book. i laughed my head off at time. i thought i would be angrier reading
column5: but then i'm already pretty angry over a lot of the topics
column6: so it was more of a soothing ""you're not the only one"" feeling. in any case so many pages marked in this book!

column1: fun story: i left it out on my desk at work one day
column3: to see what would happen. one of my male colleagues eyed it and then commented how great it looked (the design is beautiful) but rather obvislously did nor dare to get into the subject matter. 😄 and my boss (not a sexist at all)  commented something along the lines
column4: why feminism had to be everywhere currently. but he did pick a moment with two of the most unproblematic
column6: strong women i know in the room and all three of us just gave him the look. 😂

column1: 5740;instagram;2019-03-02 13:54:29;FALSE;"it's been a long time coming but i'm happy to announce after months apart and a year and a half in transition
column2: keeva and i are both together
column3: home and happy with our little spot of the woods in connecticut.

column1: last year this time i was very ill
column3: and trying to find my way back to a new normal without knowing what that could mean.

column1: now i'm a substitute teacher at an arts magnet elementary school. i hear tiny voices squeal 'ms. beeeeeeeeeeeee!' when i walk around the halls. i get hugs (and tears)
column2: stories and questions all day long. i get to impart mindfulness and self-care techniques with my tiny friends and watch them understand new perspectives.

column1: my fridge is now covered in drawings
column2: a fridge in a beautiful house i get to share with my wonderful partner

column1: living with multiple chronic illnesses means i'm never not 'sick'. working in an elementary school means i'm never far from a stomach bug or two - the running count is two within 7 weeks - but living with someone who loves me despite the things i can't help
column2: who listens to all my complaints and worries
column3: is there for all my midnight diabetes low blood sugars and ptsd triggers
column4: has made all the difference. for the first time in a very
column5: very long time i feel mostly whole
column6: happy and optimistic about the future. the view is pretty damned good from this little patch of the world.

column1: according to the domestic violence awareness project
column2: roughly 1.5 million high school students in the united states will experience physical abuse during a relationship.  approximately 25 percent of parents don’t discuss domestic violence with their teens.

column1: teen dating violence awareness month is an opportunity to start the conversation around healthy and safe relationships. encourage your community to prevent this type of violence.

what could this look like for your community? perhaps it's encouraging your school to provide educational opportunities on healthy vs unhealthy relationships.  it could also be sitting down with your teenager and engaging in an open conversation about love equaling respect in relationships.
are you interested in having dap’s outreach education specialist speak at your school
column3: business or community organization to provide preventative education on domestic violence and available resources to victims? call dap’s main office at 610-565-6272 or email npowell@dapdc.org for more information.

column2: rajkumar hirani invited to be a part of ficci frames?

column1: image source - deccan heraldthe #metoo movement shook the entire bollywood industry after several big names were called out. the likes of sajid khan
column3: alok nath and subhash ghai were accused of sexual misconduct. it all started after tanushree dutta accused nana patekar of harassing her on the sets of ‘horn ok pleassss’. rajkumar hirani too was accused by a woman who had worked with him on the sets of ‘sanju’.rajkumar denied the allegations and put out a statement that read
column4: “i was completely shocked when these allegations were brought to my notice about two months back. i had suggested immediately that it is essential to take this matter to any committee or legal body. the complainant has chosen to go to the media instead. i want to very strongly state that this is a false malicious and mischievous story being spread with the sole intention of destroying my reputation.”now
column5: it is being reported that he will be a part of ficci frames. it is to be noted that several actors and directors had to quit their projects midway
column6: because of #metoo allegations. thankfully for him
column7: hirani was not shooting for any film at that moment.clarifying their stance…

column1: 5773;instagram;2019-03-02 14:29:30;FALSE;"it’s been a little over a year since i made the very hard decision to start injecting myself every 2 weeks with a biologic
column2: seeing my rheumatologist every two months and having my blood drawn monthly.

column1: there are times i get bugged that i didn’t know sooner that i had as or that there was a treatment to help with the undeniable end of the disease.
then i remember i can’t look in the rear view mirror... i can only go forward.
humira is a tool in my arsenal. it’s not a cure. ***take away.....listen to your body
column3: educate yourself and don’t expect your dr or healthcare providers to be miracle workers.

column1: 5792;instagram;2019-03-02 14:48:07;FALSE;"“the ‘r’ word” is the latest piece from jamie (@jamieandboo_art). as with all of jamie’s work
but for those that we’ve met in the four months we’ve been on this journey
column2: jamie’s work has provided comfort and a sense of hope for people who’ve not only experienced sexual violence; but also those that have suffered from depression and mental health issues and continue to do so.

column1: it’s been a moving and humbling experience to see the impact that jamie’s work is already having. and we’ll continue to push boundaries
column2: challenge conventions and speak uncomfortable truths in our quest to start a conversation that brings about actual change.

column1: the work we’re doing with specific charities will also form part of that quest for change. a change in behaviour and a change in attitude towards those that can feel isolated and excluded because of what they’ve faced and continue to face on a daily basis.
it just leaves us to say a huge thank you to everyone that has supported us thus far and please don’t be afraid to show your support in the future.

“don’t be ashamed of your story. it will inspire others.” stigma doesn’t end on its own
column2: the change begins with courageous people who take the first steps towards discussion and normalization.  posting on social media that you are/have been going through a difficult mental health journey is not easy for many of us. that is why we are reposting this video of @luluafk to show people that you can seem completely happy
column4: and confident when you’re actually going through what many others are going through behind closed doors. social media is not an accurate representation of real life. the best advice we can give anyone reading this is that it is absolutely fine to advise and discuss your mental health journey/experience even if you aren’t where you want to be. thank you lulu for your post
column5: it may not seem like a big deal to some but it truly is in the grand scheme of things. imagine how many people would be less ashamed of asking for help when they see friends/family/influencers sharing their own experiences with it.  don't forget
column6: we are always here to listen
column8: and support (with full confidentiality and trust)

〰 what works for some may not necessarily work for you

column1: good girls celebrate international women’s day| 08.03.19
the 8th march is international women’s day
column2: so what better day to host a special gged event? come join us at the fabulous design museum
column3: where we’ll be serving up searcys cuvee
column4: delicious finger food and 3 incredible speakers.

column1: tickets available from link in bio.

all guests are welcome to take a look around the permanent exhibition before moving to the kitchen where we’ll serve up delicious searcys food plus three speakers who’ll be giving their take on how much of their career
column3: was down to design - and how much was down to luck or judgement.

column1: dagmara kodlubanski - a director and filmmaker - currently completing her exciting film project
column3: in collaboration with passion pictures. we still rise is a feature length documentary about the women’s march that took place on january 21st 2017
column4: the day after trump was inaugurated. it's a film that captures the moment the torch for #metoo was lit. (we’ll be screening a 4 minute trailer of the film on the night). 💥

column2: editorial and portraiture. inspired by people who break boundaries and are not afraid to lead the change
column3: they explore diversity and equality in a timeless style with an edge
column4: always pushing and allowing for their subject's personality and story to shine through 📸 .
